<a href="http://www.observatoire-des-aliments.fr/environnement/peche-en-eaux-profondes-lopinion-publique-contre" target="_self">http://www.observatoire-des-aliments.fr/environnement/peche-en-eaux-prof...</a></p><p>Bloom, ‘Auchan “suspend” la commercialisation d’espèces profondes’, 23&nbsp;December 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.bloomassociation.org/auchan-suspend-la-commercialisation-despeces-profondes/" target="_self">http://www.bloomassociation.org/auchan-suspend-la-commercialisation-desp...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Thanks to pressure from the EU fishing sector, the initial EC proposal to ban outright deep-sea bottom trawling was not endorsed by the European Parliament, and is likely to be diluted even further when examined in the coming months by the Council of Ministers, who are traditionally more sensitive to the socioeconomic arguments presented by the fishing sector than to environmental issues. Thus, at the policy level, the continuation of deep-sea bottom trawling – even if more regulated – is ensured. Despite this, the massive mobilisation of public opinion, particularly in France, led most French retailers to announce that they will not sell fish caught by deep-sea bottom trawls. For ACP countries wanting to maintain or increase access to the EU market for their fish products, this underlines that consumers’ opinion is just as influential as the elaboration of EU legislation. It also suggests that ACP producers should work with stakeholders along the value chain to familiarise EU retailers and consumers with their products’ quality, particularly in terms of environmental sustainability.</p>
		</div>
		
